# TOC anchor and link constraints

Contract: [shared-docs-precedence](shared-docs-precedence.mdc)

## When the rule applies

- This rule uses Agent Requested mode (`alwaysApply: false`, no `globs`); Cursor loads it when TOC formatting is relevant.
- Apply when adding, editing, or formatting a Markdown table of contents (format and anchors).
- Default is to omit a TOC unless **When to include a table of contents** below applies.

## Behavior

**Triggers:** `shared-docs-toc`, `shared-toc`, `table of contents`, `toc rules`, `toc layering`, `toc scope`

### When to include a table of contents

**Default:** Do **not** add a TOC from heading count or generic markdown rules alone. GitHub and many renderers expose an outline from headings.

**Include or refresh a TOC only when something below explicitly applies:**

- The **user** asks for a TOC, navigation block, or equivalent structure.
- A **task or playbook** states that the deliverable must include a TOC (read that scope literally).
- An existing file already has a `**Table of contents**` block — keep it accurate when adding, removing, or renaming headings, unless the user asks to remove the TOC.

TOC inclusion decisions follow the layer ordering in `shared-docs-precedence.mdc`. Path-specific rules override TOC inclusion for their governed paths. Within any layer, TOC format and anchors always follow this file (`shared-docs-toc.mdc`).

### Single-heading documents

When a TOC is already present or explicitly requested and the document has an H1 but no `##` or deeper headings,
emit the `**Table of contents**` label in the usual early placement and omit the bullet list.
Do not add a label-only TOC to a single-heading document that does not already have one.

### Format

- Place the TOC early in the document (after the intro/summary wrapper) and before the first substantive section.
- Use `**Table of contents**` with no trailing `:` as the label (bold phrase, not a heading).
- If a spec chooses to nest TOC entries by heading level, indent list items to match heading level (for example `#` = no indent, `##` = one indent, `###` = two indents). If a spec chooses a flat list, it may omit indentation while still following the same slug and link-text constraints.

### TOC entries

**Same-Document Anchors.**

- Use an unordered list of Markdown links to same-document anchors: `- [Link text](#slug)`
- Do not include semicolons (`;`) in link text or in the list line body
- Link text is plain words only; no italics, bold, or backticks inside `[...]`
- TOC anchors are the same-document heading slugs generated from the heading text

### Slug rules

**Heading Anchors.**

- Slugs are lowercase
- Spaces become hyphens
- Punctuation is stripped
- Hyphens are collapsed (multiple hyphens become one)
- Collisions use `-1`, `-2`, etc based on first occurrence order

### Tool-name headings: canonical URL stays in body

- If a section title names a tool/product that needs a canonical URL, the TOC entry still uses plain heading words
- Put the canonical URL in the section body opening prose, not in the heading or TOC

## Examples

Example: TOC entry line — `- [Install](#install)` with plain words in the label.

